      <hedline>
        <hl1>And No More Catalogs!</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Charles Tidd letter comments on Jan 20 article on opting out of direct mail offerings</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Don't Call. Don't Write. Let Me Be'' (Your Money, Jan. 20):</p>
        <p>Since early December 2006, I have received 136 different catalogs in the mail. I have called each company and asked it to take my name off the mailing list and discontinue sending me catalogs.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Don't Call. Don't Write. Let Me Be'' (Your Money, Jan. 20):</p>
        <p>Since early December 2006, I have received 136 different catalogs in the mail. I have called each company and asked it to take my name off the mailing list and discontinue sending me catalogs.</p>
        <p>In almost 100 percent of my calls, the person who answered has said courteously that the company would take my name off its mailing list.</p>
        <p>Let's see what actually happens I am now looking at 47 unwanted solicitations and am replying with a note asking them to discontinue their mailings.</p>
        <p>The most satisfying aspect of this is sending back my request in their postage-paid envelopes.</p>
        <p>Charles Tidd  Newtown, Conn., Jan. 20, 2007</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
